# Realistic Example: Identity Mempool + Deterministic Legal Signature & Evidence
## HD-derived identity (portable, verifiable, reproducible) + contracts with mathematically reconstructible evidence

This example defines a deterministic infrastructure for:

- creating HD-derived identities,
- authenticating users and organizations without rigid centralization,
- reusing KYC as a portable asset,
- signing contracts/documents with verifiable evidence,
- and reconstructing the full history of identity and legal interactions.

Core thesis:

> identity is not a stored profile; it is a deterministic tree of verifiable states.  
> a legal signature is not a stored PDF; it is a canonical, hashed, signed, and reproducible object.

---

# 1. System objective

The system solves two traditionally separate problems:

## 1.1 Deterministic identity and authentication
- HD-derived identity,
- portable across services,
- cryptographically verifiable,
- reproducible from a root,
- governed by state transitions and policies.

## 1.2 Deterministic legal signature and evidence
- signed contracts,
- canonical payloads,
- stable hashes,
- signature history,
- reconstructible evidence,
- verifiable integrity without relying on a single stored file.

